existing resources by implementing the right bottleneck-releasing projects cost-effectively. Second, developing countries will need to raise the funds necessary to close the infrastructure financing gap. As the scope for increasing government spending may be limited in many developing countries and official development assistance (ODA) flows are unlikely to increase in the near future, developing countries will need to look for new innovative financing mechanisms. They could follow the example of recent infrastructure financing initiatives in advanced economics, such as the National Infrastructure Reinvestment Bank in the United States and the Europe 2020 Project Bond Initiative, which use existing resources to attract additional private sector financing. Moreover, governments will need to reduce the risk borne by private investors. The international community could play an important role in assisting countries in overcoming these constraints through targeted financial resources and technical assistance.

